√âglise Saint-Augustin is a magnificent church located in the 8th arrondissement of Paris. Completed in 1871, it combines Romanesque and Byzantine architectural styles, and is notable for its large dome and intricate facade. The church's interior is equally impressive, featuring beautiful stained glass windows and detailed sculptures. It stands as both a significant religious site and a historical landmark in Paris.

It may not be as colourful as the Saint-Germain church, but it is better suited for sitting on a chair and praying in peace. Nonetheless, it is just as glorious and magnificent in terms of architecture, grandeur and decorations. It was an ecstatic experience for me.

Always like to run into random fascinating building while walking in the streets. Found this one on a Sunday, just before they closed the doors.  The in and outside are very impressive. If you are in the area, definitely nice to walk in and gaze at the walls, ceiling, and all the art and religious decoration.
The church was built between 1860 and 1871 by architect Victor Baltatd, designed to be a landmark between two large boulevards it can be seen from Arc de Tiomphe.

This neo-Romanesque church of XIX is really impressive. It dominates the area and from inside the darkness with huge space gives you the feeling of Byzantine churches, albeit art is very much typical catholic XIX-XX century style. Pay attention to metal constructions and ornaments (flavour of Art Noveau). I‚Äôve never seen such mix before.
Very beautiful. Diverse, with dedicated chapels and history expositions. The gold structure over the main altar makes an spectacular view beneath the cupola.
Amazing church. The building architecture is beautiful. The indoor architecture and design are so lovely.
Saint-Augustin Church of Paris is off the usual tourist track but it's a masterpiece of architecture and technology of the time. Walls and some are supported by metal columns.

not so famous church in paris thats why there are less people in this one but i would highly recommend coming here if able to. its off the beaten path. i came upon it when i dared to walk from sacre coure to the Eiffel tower. it is close to the George V area. Cool walk.  the middle section was spectacular and its surrounded by staircases to its left and right going down. its not accessible to the public though but still found it so intriguing and beautiful. feel like ive seen it in the da vinci movie.

a church where you fell closer to God, if you have enough faith

very nice church

So beautiful.
